  "prompt": "Does four wheel drive consume more fuel than two wheel drive?",
  "response": "Generally, four-wheel drive (4WD) vehicles consume more fuel than two-wheel drive (2WD) vehicles. This is because:\n\n1. Additional weight: 4WD systems add extra components and weight to the vehicle, which requires more energy to move.\n\n2. Increased drivetrain complexity: More mechanical components are engaged, creating more friction and resistance.\n\n3. Constant power distribution: 4WD systems often send power to all wheels continuously, even when not needed, increasing fuel consumption.\n\nThe fuel efficiency difference can range from 1-2 miles per gallon to more significant variations depending on the specific vehicle and driving conditions. However, modern 4WD systems have become more efficient, and some can switch between 2WD and 4WD modes to improve fuel economy.\n\nFactors like driving terrain, vehicle design, and driving habits also influence fuel consumption, so the exact difference varies between individual vehicles.",
